      <bioghist id="aspace_8f613d802370d79e2b31c4f16fcd3d10">
         <head>LINCOLN MACVEAGH (1890-1972)</head>
         <p>Lincoln MacVeagh was born October 1, 1890, in Narragansett Pier, Rhode Island. After graduating from Harvard and completing further studies at  the Sorbonne, MacVeagh served in the U. S. Army during World War I, attaining the rank of Major. After leaving military service, MacVeagh was the president of Henry Holt and Company, and then in 1923, he went on to found Dial Press.</p>
         <p>MacVeagh's first ambassadorial appointment was Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary to Greece, in 1933, serving in Athens. Subsequent appointments include Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary to Iceland 1941-1942), Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary to South Africa 1942-1943). He also served concurrent appointments as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to Greece (1943-1947) and Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to Yugoslavia (1943).</p>
         <p>Later appointments included Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to Portugal (1948-1952) and Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to Spain (1952-1953). MacVeagh retired in 1953 from government service and joined Henry Hold and Company as a director.</p>
         <p>Lincoln MacVeagh died on January 15, 1972, in Adelphi, Maryland.</p>
      </bioghist>
